<br>
Nysa recently gave birth to twin daughters, one half-elf (Loreli) and another Tier'dal (Dalninil). The half-elf is a natural child, but the Tier'dal is a creation of strange magics, with the soul of a deceased priestess of Innoruuk. Despite this, Nysa loves both equally and tries to raise them as best she can.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Description<br>
<br>
Nysa is a peaceful priestess of Erolissi Marr, and now an elder of the Circle of Sisters. She is devoted to her friends, and thrives in the company of others. She is devoted to her goddess as well, but does not always agree with the leaders of her faith, particularly the priests in the Temple of Marr in Freeport. Nysa steadfastly refuses to resort to violence, and never carries a weapon, even when travelling alone. She has two half-sisters, Bridh and Rowynia.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Background<br>
<br>
Nysa spent her early adulthood in the Temple of Marr learning from the priestesses of Erolissi. Though quiet at first, her curiosity triumphed over her shyness once she grew more comfortable with the sisterhood of the goddess. Eventually she could be found wandering the religious precincts of North Freeport, questioning everyone she could meet. Though she did not always understand what others had to say, she was always willing to listen. Only a few would notice that she would rarely speak of her own past.<br>
<br>
Though she loved the temple, Nysa worried that she was too isolated from the troubles that plagued Norrath, and wanted to see more of the world. The teachings of Erolissi compelled her to help others, and Nysa also did not want to be a burden on the temple. The priests of Marr were opposed to her leaving, feeling that she was not prepared for the dangers she might face. As those responsible for her debated the issue, she quietly slipped into the night, saying goodbye only to her closest friends.<br>
<br>
Nysa's first few months on the streets of Freeport were not easy. Though hungry and cold, Nysa refused to return to the shelter of the temple, fearing she would never be able to leave again. In time, she found that easy work could be had in the underside of the city, provided that she curbed her impulse to ask too many questions. In the company of these rogues and scoundrels, Nysa learned the story of the other side of the city, a story very different from the one told by the Knights of Truth.<br>
<br>
After a while she found more respectable work as an apprentice smith in East Freeport, and was able to earn enough money to wonder about leaving the city itself. Her first few excursions outside the gates terrified her. Everywhere there was violence and death. Nysa remained determined to stand on her own and help where she could, and she soon found that she could travel more safely in the company of other adventurers.<br>
<br>
Nysa is now carefully learning more about the greater world of Norrath. She marvels at the land's terrors and its wonders, and relishes the secrets that she learns. She cherishes the stories of her traveling companions, and wants nothing more than to help them discover their destinies, and perhaps her own.<br>
<br>
