<br>
Since his loss of his powers, Pryce has seemed perhaps a bit... off.  He seems to look a bit different, but perhaps it's just that his facial hair has been shaved off.<br>
<br>
DESCRIPTION<br>
<br>
Pryce is a koada'dal enchanter with platinum hair and strange lilac eyes.  He comes off at first as very serious, formal, and high-elf-ish, but quickly shows an impish side and loves nothing more than to change his form to amuse others and infiltrate strange places.  He revels in his power at times and can be quite imperious.  His pride and joy is Pryce's Emporium, his traveling jewelcraft shop.  He often speaks of jewelcraft (and enchanting, to a lesser extent) as his Art with a pronounced *capital* &quot;A;&quot; and little seems more important to him than the perfection and marketing of his Art - his reputation is built upon jewelcrafting, and it seems to be the heart of his self-esteem.<br>
<br>
BACKGROUND<br>
<br>
While he is a koada'dal who, at times, casually references a lifespan of 300 or more years, no one to whom you have spoken in the Faydark has met Pryce before he set up his Emporium outside the gates of Felwithe a scant few months ago.  He is not forthcoming about his past, often choosing, when pressed, to change the subject or change his form as a distraction.<br>
<br>
He was brought (half eager, half kicking and screaming) into the Clan of Brothers by the paladin Raen, for whom he clearly has a sisterly affection, and he's often seen in the company of Temolin the bard and Kelthalas the ranger.  Once an unhappy follower of the god Karana, Pryce apparently performed the arcane Rites of Separation to renounce the hold Karana had on him, but lost all his powers and skills in the process; this was very traumatic for him.  Various of the Brothers and Sisters helped him to his feet, cementing his (at first ambivalent) loyalty to the guilds, and Pryce is often seen doing intensive re-training with Briarboots Bandylegs in order to regain his lost powers.<br>
<br>
The training has fully taken, and Pryce has overtaken and leapt past his former skill at a shocking pace.  Pryce's Emporium is once again open, with a wider selection of wares than it had before.  But Pryce's newfound good humor is lately contrasted with sudden bursts of reclusiveness. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=20371A><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/ueqnysa.showPublicProfile?language=EN>eqnysa</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Mistress of Imagination<br>Elder</span><br>  Posts: 472<br> <font color=#660000>(3/9/02 12:06:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fcircleofsistersfrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=176.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Minuet's Background</span><hr size=1> [Moved by Nysa]<br>
<br>
Minuet gently ran the oilcloth over the neck of her mandolin, massaging out the dirt and dust and, was that a new scratch? Many a time she had to resort to bashing a foe over the head with it when she was caught unarmed. Luckily it was a master crafted instrument, her father had said it was luthiered by Nostrolo himself. Minuet sang one of her father's favorite songs, as she attempted her best to deal with the new ding in her instrument.<br>
<br>
&quot;As he saw his life run away from him, thousands ran along,<br>
Chanting words from a song.<br>
As he saw his life run away from him, thousands ran along,<br>
Chanting words from a song.<br>
Please me have no regrets,<br>
Please me have no regrets.<br>
Came from the baby's mouth.<br>
We follow the lines going South.&quot;<br>
<br>
Her father had passed on the instrument to her before his death. He had lived a full life but had grown old rapidly as mortal men were want to do. With her mother's Elven heritage, Minuet was assured of living considerably longer then any human lover she could perhaps choose. She harboured doubts about a future with a single, let alone human, mate, especially after she witnessed the pain that he mother had endured at her father's passing. After her father died, her mother, Elliadril, started the Elven mourning period and she had taken Minuet from Qeynos over the sea to the forests of Faydwer. There she was able to meet more of her cousins and be schooled in the lore or her mother's lineage. Her Elven cousins laughed at her Qeynos accent and found her to be a quick-witted companion as they tolerated her bastardization of the Hometongue. She spent time mastering her father's mandolin and would wander through the heights of Kelethin, listening to the People's music, and picking out the tunes on the well aged wood.<br>
<br>
The pleasure of those languorous days was broken by the onslaught of the Crushbone Orcs, who had conspired with the Tier Dal and had come out of the Butcherblock Mountains in foul hordes after decade of relative serenity. So massive were their numbers that they were able to establish a foothold in the Greater Faydark and from there continually threaten the peace of her mother's home. Several of Minuet's cousins fell in the battles against the orc hordes, and it was a trying time for all. Minuet had intended to join the Guardians of the Faydark when she came of age, and stand with her cousins to protect their homeland. But that was not to be.<br>
<br>
Elliadril called Minuet into her chambers one cool fall evening. There had been a recent thrust from the orcs and it had been a long trying week, safeguarding the walls of Felwithe from the seemingly limitless mass of orcs that besieged it. Elliadril took Minuet's hand in her own. Her mother's beautiful face was worn and tired. She had been using her skills as a healer to assist and fortify the city's guardians, and it was a constant drain on her mother's strength. But there was something else in her face tonight that brought worry to Minuet.<br>
<br>
&quot;My beautiful child, how strange these times must be for you,&quot; her mother's voice was soothing. &quot;I had hoped that you would live your life unburdened by such violence and bloodshed, but that is not always meant to be. I regret that I must add another burden to your life. I have received the calling and must travel west, to Elvenholme. I will leave soon, when Luclin smiles again. This is a journey that you cannot make with me, as you are your father's daughter, and are meant to truly live among his kin. You are close enough of age now where you are able to choose your own path. You may remain here or return to Qeynos and our home there. If you wish for us to have a little more time together, we can journey to Qeynos, as it is from there that I will meet the vessel that will take me Elvenholme.&quot;<br>
<br>
Not wanting to leave her mother's side so soon, Minuet chose to travel with her back to Qeynos. The trip was bittersweet, as her bond with Elliadril only became stronger as they traveled and talked, her mother now speaking to her much more as the woman she was becoming and less as the curious child of the past. The arrival home came only too quickly. Their house in Qeynos had been closed up for some time, her father's tools cobwebbed and nest of pigeons taking advantage of a hole in the eaves. They spent her mother's last days there cleaning up the house, now Minuet's, and watching the sunset on the sea to the west. The departure was a tearful one for Minuet, as she watched the beautiful Elven ship depart the Qeynos docks and disappear into the horizon.<br>
<br>
&quot;And I can't decide, if this place is make-believe,<br>
Worked all my life, to turn sleet to snow.<br>
We will turn our heads into the sunset,<br>
As the storms rage in the East.<br>
And we're goin down to see my lady love.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Now I'm not really interested,<br>
In telling you my mind.<br>
Just let me drag another before you go,<br>
I'm a broken wire.<br>
Now nobody knows where to find us,<br>
And it ain't nobody's loss.&quot;<br>
<br>
Minuet finished her song, to the modest applause of the crowd at Windspirit's Song. Many of them were accomplished minstrels in their own right but they had been supportive of Minuet and offered her patronage since the day she wandered into the Qeynos Bardic College. She had not been long in discovering her true calling, and felt that for the time, things were as they should be.<br>
<br>
Now, sitting in the shadow of the gigantic Combine spires, that performance seemed a lifetime ago. Minuet finished caring for her mandolin and wrapped it affectionately in its fur-lined shroud. Glancing briefly at the sunset, Minuet sped off in blur of light and sound, to the east.<br>
<br>
Minuet the Talechaser<br>
The enchanting half-elf bard of Qeynos.<br>
