<br>
&quot;My story?  I am unsure of where to even begin such a task as telling my story.  For myself, it started many of your years ago, in a place I now find myself struggling to call home.  To start at the beginning would only lead to confusion and disbelief.  I am no bard, and I do not think I am capable of looking back on my life, then reciting it as epic poetry, a tale of intrigue and drama that no other story could hope to rival.<br>
<br>
I feel I must begin by informing you that I am not of your world.  I come from the place you would most likely refer to as ‘Heaven’ although we call it nothing of the sort.  I will keep this portion of the story as brief as I can, if only because my home is impossible to describe in mortal words.  Even if I could, it would take me years upon years to tell all I felt I needed to tell, as there are countless details within my story that I do not even touch upon here, all of which have impacted my life as much as any other.  But I should remain on my story as it relates to Norrath as much as possible.<br>
<br>
I was born many hundreds of your years ago.  A vast majority of my time was spent with either my best friend, Erollisi (who, upon arriving in Norrath I find is worshipped as a Goddess!  You can only imagine my surprise!) or my love, who’s mortal name is unknown to me.  A great deal of the time was also, not fully by my own choice, spent with the company of Mithaniel Marr. I do care about him because he is like a brother to myself… a very obnoxious brother that would like nothing more than to see me squirm.  Most of the time, he seemed to plan his evenings around pestering Erollisi and myself.  But still, I do love him as only a sister can.  I suppose there are few older brothers who did not act as he did while growing up.  He certainly has his good side, which is the side that his mortal followers know. However, I find it difficult to deal with those who would worship him!  I do not mean offense against his followers when my tongue gets sharp after I have been ‘Given the blessings of Mithaniel Marr and his eternal protection’ but knowing he is worshipped as a God… disturbs me.  How would you feel to know that your bully of an older brother is worshipped by hundreds of thousands?!  Having been forced to grow up with him has skewed my perspective.  As grand and honorable as he was in your land, I can still see him hiding in the bushes throwing mud balls and Erollisi and myself while we lay on our backs admiring the sunset.  As I said, my feelings on the matter are biased having known him as a child, so you may pay them little mind.<br>
<br>
I am sorry, I have become sidetracked.  I only wished to clear up a few misconceptions regarding my feelings for Mithaniel that I have come across in my travels.  I shall return to relating my story to Norrath.  Your land was mythical to us, much like mine is to you.  I knew few of my kind who had ever had such a grand adventure as to travel to your world, but one I knew quite well was Mithaniel.  He, I strongly assume, is the reason Erollisi is known to Norrath.  (She will be most displeased with him when she finds out!)  Mithaniel returned to us with the stories I touched upon earlier.  Stories of adventures to scourge evil from the land, sacrifices made for the well being of others, and the beautiful loves that can only be read about in faerie tales!  ‘Such an interesting place this Norrath must be!’ I thought to myself.<br>
<br>
My love thought the same.  Mithaniel, being much older than the rest of us, returned to your lands again and again. At the time, my kind was not unaccustomed to taking the form of a mortal and descending to Norrath (Although it was not very common.  As I said, I knew few who had done so.  Becoming mortal is a skill that requires such precision that very few of my kind have mastered it, and finding a… ‘Priest’ who can perform such a task can be difficult for most of us.)  He would take the physical form of a mortal while retaining his ‘Angelic’ qualities.  (Again, ‘Angel’ is a word that I find best fits what a mortal would call us.  It is not a very accurate term.) <br>
<br>
Mithaniel’s deeds of valor in defense of the land became legendary, and he soon had several others who wished to venture to Norrath to do battle with the forces of evil.  One of those several was my love.  To enter your lands, we must, as I briefly mentioned earlier, temporarily give up our immortal bodies.  We must leave our bodies behind in Heaven and become, in essence, a mortal.  We must be reborn, although this birth requires no mother.  The priest can fashion a mortal body and allow our spirits to enter.  This body begins as all others, as a small child.  When our spirit returns to heaven, the mortal body dies, therefore every return trip to your land must start as a child again.  (Although I have heard rumors that our leaders know of ways to return to your land at any time in any form, and I certainly do not doubt them.  Our leaders and those close to them are quite powerful indeed!)<br>
<br>
But I stray from how this relates to me.  My love wished to share in the adventures of your land.  I begged for him to stay, and the amount of tears I cried over the matter could have flooded the Plains of Karana!  But he had made up his mind.  He, along with the others, were to go to Norrath and purge the lands of evil.  They found a priest who agreed to give them mortal bodies.  The ‘Priest’ was quite well respected for his ability to send multiple spirits at once.<br>
<br>
But all did not go well.  I cannot pretend to understand the procedure and all that went wrong, but I know, in the heat the chaos, the priest and his assistants were in a panic to either pull spirits back into their rightful bodies or quickly force them into their mortal forms.  This was done, as was explained to me, to prevent any of the spirits from becoming lost.  The mortal bodies were scattered across your lands in the confusion, as their location was irrelevant next to the need to force the spirit in.  It took several of your years to sort through the mess, during which time our leaders banned the practice of becoming mortal without their direct permission.  We waited for each of the forced mortals to become an age in which they were mature enough to fully understand what they truly were.  These angels, after this epiphany, simply returned to Heaven.  In the end, all were accounted for… all save one; my love.<br>
<br>
I was told his spirit was one of those forced into a mortal body, except his body had not fully developed into what we need; a mortal body with a few ‘alterations’ making it capable of comprehending an angel’s memory.  Without such, an angel, as had been theorized at the time, would simply forget what they were, and believe themselves to be mortal. The body would be strong enough to reject the incomprehensible information, but not yet strong enough to accept it.  This is what happened with my love.  He would never reach the age of remembrance.  He would never be able to contact Heaven on his own.  He would live as a mortal… and die as one.  They assured me there was a ‘chance’ his spirit would, upon his death, be able to return to his immortal body and live as the angel I knew again.  But this is still unknown.  The land was searched for him, in the hopes that he could be found, but those hopes proved to be in vain.  He was now indistinguishable from any other mortal.  We knew not his appearance, his voice, his name. <br>
<br>
They eventually gave up their search.  I however, did not.  I pleaded to the leaders to allow me to become mortal so I may search for him.  I was quickly rejected… but Tunare took me aside and sympathized with my situation.  It was she who sent my spirit into this mortal body. (Although Erollisi gave me my name!)  I was warned however, and that warning implanted into my mortal soul.  Although it embarrasses me to say such, my voice is recognized throughout Heaven.  Unimaginable beauty they say.  (I do not say.  I think I only sound like me, which I figure to be quite normal.)  For a fellow angel to say such is exceptional compliment though.  As a mortal mind is incapable of understanding the thoughts and memories of an angel, a mortal mind, I am told, is incapable of comprehending the immeasurable beauty within my voice.  To hear such beauty, I am told, would be equivalent to a mortal seeing Heaven.  This, to put it simply, is not possible.  It would result in immediate death for the mortal.  The mortal mind cannot handle such an overload of emotion.<br>
<br>
Because of this, I find myself unable to speak with anyone in Norrath.  My body was formed to be acceptable to a mortal’s comprehension, but to alter my voice would require altering my spirit, and that was a risk I could not even being to consider, and Tunare certainly would not have allowed it regardless!  My appearance is a simple mortal representation of my immortal body, and I was to be a High Elf of Felwithe.  However, for unknown reasons (My sister tells me it was my desire to begin searching for my love that caused me to wander away) I was found in Greater Faydark by a young Wood Elf known as Alyissa.  Alyissa was of eight years of age and already an adventurer at heart.  She frequently ran through the forest dreaming of grandeur.  I was raised with the family as their own, which is why I call her my sister.<br>
<br>
And that, I suppose, is my story.  I have been here for twenty-three of your years, during which time I do not have contact with Heaven.  I may go home once, and from then on, I shall never be allowed to return to Norrath.  A compromise Tunare was forced to make with the other leaders to allow me this chance.  I have lived at my home in Kelethin, learning the ways of the world until recently.  Now I find myself old enough, mature enough, and knowledgeable enough in your ways to truly begin my search.  Although, I must admit, I harbor a great deal of doubt, both concerning my ability to ever find my love, and my true feelings for him.  Even if I do find him, I am now unsure of what that may mean.  So many years of uncontrollable thoughts. Would he still love me?  Would I find him with another?  Would I still love him?  I cannot ever forget that he intended to come to Norrath at the price of breaking my heart and leaving me behind alone.&quot;<br>
