<br>
Now, be honest. Why'd ye want to know that? More over, what makes ye think I'd tell ye the truth at all? Ye know what I do to make my livin', aye? But if ye're sure?<br>
<br>
All right then. Ye'll get a story. Some of it's hearsay from when I was too young to remember, and ye must keep in mind the barmaids and innkeeps of Freeport are nae too concerned with facts if they'll get in the way of a tale. But aye, pull up a seat and pour yerself a drink, ye great glutton for punishment, and I'll fill ye in on all the gossip.<br>
<br>
Mead? No? Dinnae look at me like that, the sand and seaweed wipes right off, it does. Sure I hauled the case up from a wreck on the seabed, but the bottles were sound and the price was right.<br>
<br>
Still no? All right, then. Yer loss.<br>
<br>
Now then, coming up on twenty years ago, there was one of the finest fishing vessels Freeport had ever seen, the Perdition's Twilight, and her captain was a man with rough hands and a good heart named Aurik Oarsbinder. Aurik and his crew fished the Ocean of Tears, most weeks, as the schools run fast there, and most years, a ship's nets are not long empty when dragged in those waters. But this autumn twenty years back? Prexus must have been stirring in his great briny bed beneath the waves, as something had chased nearly all the fish away, and the Twilight could barely pull in enough scales to feed her own crew, much less turn a profit on returnin' to Freeport.<br>
<br>
Aurik, though, was a canny man, and he had nae become a captain of his own ship without knowing a thing or two about fishin'. With the unseasonable warmth of that October, he guessed that the fish had gone north for more comfortable climes, and guessed right as well! No sooner had the Twilight spread her nets north of Faydwer than the fish began practically leaping onto the deck. The haul was so good that the crew decided to risk weathering the gathering storm for a few more hours before turning back, but alas the clouds carried no ordinary burden of rain.<br>
<br>
The tales still fly of that storm, that it was as if Karana and Solusek Ro had gotten into a great bloody brawl up in the heavens: a firestorm. Nae just thunder or rain poured down, but gouts of flame, leaping from cloud to cloud and licking hungrily at the distant wooded shores of Faydwer. The sailors stared horrified, until years of nautical instinct took over. They tried to draw in the sails, but too late; a finger of cloudflame had run its talon across the mainsail, and the fabric was burning now, a sheet of fire hovering over the boat. Aurik and his crew rushed to hack the burning sail free and succeeded before the fires reached the mast. The immediate danger was past, but now they were marooned, without hope to catch the wind when the skies cleared.<br>
<br>
The crew huddled below decks until the storm cleared an hour later, just as suddenly as it had appeared. They emerged to find the tide was carrying them for the shore, so they dropped anchor before the Twilight had herself an unpleasant encounter with the rocks, and took the shuttles in to shore. Aurik knew the elven town of Kelethin was somewhere nearby, but in the dense foliage of the Faydark, they soon became disoriented, and when night set in, they were thoroughly lost. Some fashioned torches from smoldering branches left to burn by the firestorm, and they continued on their uncertain path until Aurik spotted a greater fire burning in the distance.<br>
<br>
Believing salvation to be at hand, the crew cast off caution and rushed forward, thinking of elvish hospitality and fresh sailcloth for their crippled vessel. The fire soon burned low and vanished, however, and the men were left with fear creeping back into their hearts. Nevertheless, it was the only sign they had found, and so they kept up in that direction until they reached what had been the source of that fire just as dawn began to break: the remnants of a cottage in the woods, crumbled inward and still smoking from the fire that had consumed it. As their hearts began to fall further, the still dawn air was cut by a shrill wail from within the remnants of the cottage.<br>
<br>
Most of the crew edged backwards uneasily, but Aurik shoved his torch into the hands of a shipmate and rushed forward, diving through the ruined doorway and forcing his way through the glowing embers of what remained of the house's modest furnishings. The wailing was louder now, and as Aurik hefted shelves away from the husk of the cabin's stone fireplace, he grunted in surprise as two charred corpses were revealed bellow, both captured in their last moments of agony by the flame. For a mad moment, Aurik though it had been the corpses which wailed, but the he heard the cry again, beneath them, and gently eased their bodies aside to discover a thin little bairn with slightly pointed ears and his clothes and hair singed all away.<br>
<br>
Me. Covered in ash and cinders and bawling like a pierced orc, but hale and all in one piece.<br>
<br>
Aurik grabbed me up from that hearth and clutched me to his chest, then sprang back out of the cabin just as what remained of the chimney came crashing down on what remained of the two that must have been my parents. The rest of the crew were startled to see the baby in the hands of their captain, and gather around him asking if Aurik was alright and peering at me.<br>
<br>
&quot;A babe born of ash,&quot; muttered one of them, staring at my soot-covered face.<br>
<br>
&quot;Nonsense,&quot; scoffed Aurik, and he wiped me clean as best he could, then wrapped me in his cape and cowl. Finally with a moment to spare, he turned me around to stare at him, and chuckled at the sight of my bluegreen eyes. &quot;Like me da's own likeness, he is,&quot; he said with a smile, and he named me Langrall then, after his own father.<br>
<br>
Wrapping me tighter and tucking me into his satchel, he led the others out again to continue the search for Kelethin, and in the growing daylight they fared much better. Kelethin welcomed the ragged crew and agreed to sell them the necessary sailcloth and escort them back to the Perdition's Twilight, but they would nae take me. I suppose this human's story of finding me in the woods rang a bit thin to them, and they were loathe to take in an unwanted bastard half-breed. Aurik, I think, was secretly relieved, as I believe even then he had his heart set on raising me himself.<br>
<br>
Once the Twilight was again rigged to sail, they set out home for Freeport, and Aurik brought me home to live with him and his young wife, Abigail. She looked after me kindly enough while he was away, but I dinnae think she had any great love for this foundling child, even then. I have vague memories of Aurik, though, and he was always kind to me when he was back in port. The time came, however, when the Perdition's Twilight didnae return to port. I was five, then. Word came that another firestorm had struck the Ocean of Tears, and this time the Twilight had nae been so lucky. None of her crew was ever found, and only one bit of her ever washed ashore that was recognizable.<br>
<br>
Abigail, in her grief, blamed me for the loss, and I suppose I cannae blame her. She cast me out, and I would have no doubt perished if the innkeeps and shop owners of East Freeport had nae cared so much for Aurik. They took me in for his sake, called me Ashborn 'cause of the tale of my finding, and passed me around between them to bear the burden better. An extra mouth is nae a welcome sight in the ports, but they managed. I heard later that Abigail had thrown herself into the sea in grief, the poor woman. I lived in taverns and on the docks this way until I was around ten years old and, on a lark, tried to swipe the purse of a Militia soldier. He was nae amused at my little jest, and would no doubt have dashed my little brains out upon the cobbles had good old Janam and Rebby nae been close by.<br>
<br>
Do ye know them, by the bye? They're members of the Tradesfolk of Freeport, and as fine a pair of Ne'er-do-wells as ye'll ever meet.<br>
<br>
Anyway, they smoothed the soldier's temper with a few coins, and herded me back to the Den under the docks of Freeport. They told Ellisi of the promise they had seen in my amateur attempts at pick pocketing, and soon I was trained up as one of the Tradesfolk. The salt in the blood of my adopted father had gotten into mine as well, though, and I also pulled in some honest living on the decks of Freeport's tradeships, traveling the seas abroad, but I always returned to my new family in the Den. I've a hammock of my own in one of the alcoves near the sea down there, and it's there more than anywhere where I can sleep as though I'm home.<br>
<br>
Well, there ye have it. The whole sordid lot. As I said, I cannae account for the first part of the story, as I was far too young to remember, but I will tell ye that the Perdition's Twilight did go down in the Ocean of Tears all those years ago, and there were two firestorms at just those times. Ye can check the charts in the port office yerself if ye dinnae believe me. I dinnae care much, meself; it makes a good story, aye, but I've found it makes more sense to ponder where ye're headed then where ye've been, if ye take my meaning.<br>
<br>
Especially in the cases when ye've got an irate crowd of merchants and militia members chasing ye, of course.<br>
<br>
-Langrall of Freeport<br>
Treasure Hunter Extraordinaire<br>
Professional Ne'er-do-well<br>
Expert Swordsman<br>
Inveterate Liar<br>
