<br>
Soyin crept into the hall (as she usually does) to find a single candle burning, casting its guttering yellow light throughout the room creating evil shadows dancing from table to table, chair to chair.<br>
<br>
Thinking this was a bit odd, Soyin moved towards the candle, meaning to extinguish it before retiring to her room.<br>
<br>
&quot;Soyin.&quot;<br>
<br>
Soyin jumped, then cursed the Gods silently, not liking to be caught unawares. Being surprised in such a way was detrimental to her health with the shady path she had chosen for herself. Looking over her shoulder, she relized she was indeed not alone, and that the bard Kristyl was seated in a dark corner in the back of the hall.<br>
<br>
Looking closer as she approached Kris's table, she noticed the pain evident on her young Sister's face. She had also been crying at some time recently, with red eyes and the paths of dried tears still evident. Even her hair, which normally seemed a vibrant gold seemed to be somehow subdued, and the clever grin was missing from her lips.<br>
<br>
&quot;Kristyl girl, whatever is the matter?&quot; Soyin asked, her voice full of concern.<br>
<br>
Kristyl looked down at her gnomish sister and a smile temporarily crossed her face. She loved Soyin very much, she was one of the first Sisters she had met. It has been some time since their first introductions by that underground lake near the Hole on Odus.<br>
<br>
&quot;Today is my Mother's birthday.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You must miss her very much, does she live far away?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Not far at all Soyin, for I carry her very close to me. In my heart, my mind and my very soul. She died two years ago this past winter.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Oh my, Kris I'm so sorry....&quot;<br>
<br>
Kristyl raised her hand, &quot;No no Soyin, pay it no mind. How could you know? I've never spoken of her or anything about me before, not to anyone.&quot;<br>
<br>
Soyin nodded, &quot;She must have been a wonderful person.&quot;<br>
<br>
Again Kristyl smiled at her friend, nodding her head and wiping new tears from her green eyes. Then softly, at first almost inaudibly, Kristyl began to sing. The sound began to grow in volume and texture until Soyin was amazed. <br>
<br>
She had experienced bardic magic several times over the years, but she found herself being assaulted by the power and emotion coming from this young woman's voice.<br>
<br>
She could see in her mind’s eye a human woman, slender of build but very tall, with dark eyes and flowing blonde hair. She was very beautiful and Soyin felt some of the pain that Kristyl was feeling. Then there was another in the vision, a wood elf from the look of him she thought. A proud young elf with chestnut hair and green eyes. He was quite muscular for an elf, and Soyin realized that this must be Kristyl’s Father. <br>
<br>
The song continued, at Soyin almost laughed in spite of herself when she saw a gangly adolescent Kristyl, smiling shyly at her father. It appeared that she was unaccustomed to the body she wore, moving without the grace and confidence that she has now. What made it easy to identify as her Sister was the impish grin that never left her face, and the blonde curls that acted likewise, refusing to be tucked out of the way.<br>
<br>
Images passed in front of Soyin’s eyes. Of Kristyl walking the streets (of Freeport?) and spending time with her family in some nearby forrest. Then there was a boat, no wait, several boats. It was on these vessels that Kristyl’s family approached a foreign shore while torrents of rain beat down upon them from a dark grey sky. On that shore Kristyl’s family and the other elves began construction of an outpost, but Soyin then watched in horror as the many of the elves were cut down by wave after wave of drachnid and sarnak.<br>
<br>
“Soyin.”<br>
<br>
Soyin came out of the spell that Kristyl had weaved.<br>
<br>
“My father volunteered to lead his people to establish the outpost now known as Firiona Vie. He was a great man, but not great enough to endure was he was forced to face on those foreign shores. I don’t think any man or woman was. I was only seven when the spiders came. My father fought bravely I am told, but…I never saw him again of course.”<br>
<br>
Kristyl sighed and fixed her eyes on the distant candle, it’s light reflecting in her eyes. “My Mother and I stayed for a while, helped where we could but I don’t think that she was comfortable among my Father’s people without him around to support her so we returned to her home, to Freeport. She spent the rest of her days there spreading the word of the Goddess, teaching me to help others as she did.”<br>
<br>
Kristyl paused, then looked again at Soyin. “The pain I felt from the loss of my Father, and then the inevitable loss of my Mother caused me great pain as you could imagine.”<br>
<br>
Soyin nodded.<br>
<br>
“I found that the only way I could live with this pain was through poetry…song…dance. To totally lose myself in it. To forget even who I was, even if I eventually had to return to the pain. My actions soon brought notice from the Bards of Antonnica, and even though I was never an even-tempered young bard I found that this was what I was meant to do, meant to be, and they welcomed me with open arms. Just before my Mother’s death she asked if I would continue her work, to continue to spread the word of Erollisi Marr. I told her I would of course, I would have agreed to anything because she meant everything to me.”<br>
<br>
“However, as you know, I am no Priestess. I think the Goddess would have fallen from the Heavens laughing hysterically had I decided to try.” Kristyl grinned her familiar grin. “So I chose to spread Her word my way. With song. It was only recently that I found that music had other uses besides enjoyment and art, much to my chagrin I found that music could even be used to harm others. And though I detest doing so, I have done it on occasion to those who deserve it.”<br>
<br>
Kristyl looked down on Soyin, and noticed that her poor Sister’s eyes were nearly black from lack of sleep. She laughed, “Oh Soyin, you should have stopped me ages ago, the sun is coming up.”<br>
<br>
Soyin glanced out the window and noticed that this was true, even the candle had burned itself out, how long had this bard had her under the spell of music?<br>
<br>
“Off to bed with you,” Kristyl scolded, “I’ll bother you no more. Besides, I have to get going, whenever I’m in town on a Sunday, I like to offer my voice to the Goddess for the day.”<br>
<br>
Kristyl stood up, and after trying to straighten out her hair and clothing turned back to Soyin. <br>
<br>
“Well, how do I look?” she laughed. “Horrid I know, but I’m off none the less. And Soyin, thank you for listening, you have helped me much this day.”<br>
<br>
Before Soyin could even answer, Kristyl got down on one knee and gave her a big hug. And then she was gone, faster than lightning out the door. Soyin cringed as the door slammed shut behind her. Sighing, she shook her head and turned to head of to her room when she heard something drop to the floor behind her. Turning back she noticed that the doorknob had fallen off the door.<br>
<br>
She grinned to herself, “Arania’s not going to be too happy to find out Kristyl’s broken the door again.”<br>
